replies.text:
@Thundersen-u6z if profit was the motive, they wouldn't have allowed them to write a story that alienates its original core audience, and would have opted for something boring, and inoffensive. They would have continued to play it safe, because Disney needed and still needs people to go to theatres for most of its investments to come around, and being unable to make Star Wars make money is an open fact now that destroys faith in their other projects. 

It's not about the money. It probably never was. If it was, they would have waited until someone with less personal attachment had control of star wars, and bought it cheaper, or spent more time and energy writing it than none at all. It is and basically always has been pure, xenophobic hatred for men outside the mainstream culture. Luke sold Star Wars because he hated Star Wars fans. Disney bought Star Wars so that it could hurt Star Wars fans. The writers they eventually had direct it did so in a way that intentionally ostracized and alienate you. They did this knowing that Star Wars _was_ the most beloved franchise, and considered one of the most important american myths, hitting the same heights as Gilgamesh.

They do it because they hate you. The idea that they do it for profit insinuates they really did believe they were sitting on gold plated scripts, when we know now that they didn't even have a plan internally for where the story should go. If they were operating on _profit_ they would have spent at least 500k on assurance to make sure the 500b arrives. They didn't, not because 500k is a big amount of money, but almost certainly because anyone hired to actually manage the project would immediately shoot down the attempts to burn it down, and salt the earth it stood on.

@fundhund62 They misunderstood why the prequels weren't loved by all. 
Their biggest mistake was setting off on a trilogy without a clue as to how the story would pan out. 
They've had well over a decade to get it right. Aside from Tony Gilroy, they just don't have any good writers.
